{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01UNUb4b3BeDj6jHDXnCSEPd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MAfj8kF6hi7G7khYM5Cr9j","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A Unit test with mocked data sources can verify happy-path aggregation logic, but real failures occur in error-path resilience. Specifically: if one data source times out mid-pipeline, does the code continue calling the other sources or abort silently? This requires Integration-level testing with actual HTTP behavior (timeouts, partial failures) to verify the code resilience and error handling. Unit tests with mocked success/error returns cannot reproduce real HTTP timeout scenarios or connection resets.","test_description":"Set up mock HTTP endpoints for the three data sources. Configure one endpoint to delay response (simulating timeout), and another to return a 500 error. Verify that the aggregation function continues to call all sources despite partial failures, and that the report content includes data from the two successful sources while marking the unavailable source appropriately.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires actual HTTP behavior control (timeouts, error codes) rather than mocked return values, which is Integration-level infrastructure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a 'data unavailable' note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The behavior explicitly requires graceful degradation under failure. A Unit test with mocked error returns can verify the basic logic (if error received, add note), but real failures occur with actual HTTP failure modes that mocks cannot fully reproduce: connection timeouts (not just error codes), partial/chunked responses, authentication failures, and redirect loops. Integration-level testing is needed to verify the code handles real network failure modes and continues processing.","test_description":"Configure a mock HTTP endpoint to return 503 Service Unavailable or timeout after 5 seconds. Verify the pipeline does not abort, produces a complete report with a 'data unavailable' note in the relevant section, and includes all data from the functioning sources.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Graceful degradation cannot be properly tested without actual HTTP failure modes; mocking just return values misses timeout, connection reset, and protocol-level failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior tests the summary generation logic—extracting and accurately representing values from input data. Assuming rule-based or templated summary generation (not LLM-based, as not stated in the problem), a Unit test is sufficient: create test data with known key values, call the summary generation function, assert the output contains and represents those values correctly. This catches logic bugs in value extraction and representation. If the narrative generation uses a real LLM (not explicitly stated), Agentic would be required instead.","test_description":"Create test data with specific, measurable key values (e.g., '5 critical issues filed', 'deployment success rate 87%', 'mean time to resolution 2.3 hours'). Call the summary generation function. Assert the generated summary contains these exact values accurately represented (e.g., '5 critical issues' not '50' or '0.5').","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit-level test is sufficient for rule-based summary logic. If the system uses an LLM for narrative generation, this would require Agentic-level testing instead.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This end-to-end behavior requires verification that the email actually reaches a recipient's inbox. A Unit test with mocked email service only verifies the code calls the email API correctly. An Integration test with a local mock SMTP server verifies the email is formatted and transmitted to SMTP. But real failures—email queued but never delivered, authentication failure with real provider, TLS handshake failure, email marked as spam—only surface when using actual email delivery infrastructure. System-level testing with a real or production-like email service is needed to verify the complete behavior.","test_description":"Run the full pipeline (data collection → summary generation → email delivery) using a real or test email service (e.g., AWS SES, SendGrid sandbox, or a temporary email API). Configure a test inbox. Verify the email arrives with correct recipient address, subject, body content, and formatting.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The behavior explicitly requires verifying the email 'reaches the configured recipient's inbox', which cannot be tested without actual email delivery infrastructure. Mock SMTP cannot verify inbox delivery.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior requires testing two coupled concerns: (1) file persistence under failure, and (2) retry logic across scheduled runs. A Unit test with mocked filesystem can verify the basic logic (save report, retry flag set). But real failures occur when actual filesystem operations fail: permission errors, disk full, file already exists, read errors on retry. Additionally, verifying the retry actually happens requires testing the state machine across two simulated runs. Integration-level testing with real filesystem operations and mocked scheduler timing is needed to catch these realistic failure modes.","test_description":"Mock the email service to fail (e.g., connection refused or timeout). Verify the report is written to a specific file path with correct content. Simulate a second scheduled run by calling the same script/function again. Verify the script reads the saved file and successfully retries email delivery. Confirm the saved file is cleaned up (or marked as delivered) after successful retry.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Testing file I/O and the retry loop across runs requires Integration-level infrastructure; mocking the filesystem would miss real I/O failures like permission errors or disk full scenarios.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13644,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13644},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f76edc85-c11b-49c6-aaa1-a8f5824ea3b2","uuid":"8889e916-4e4a-4efb-86ab-258e5e160cbb"}
